what is the 2>%1?
"Shell script's idiom"?
magic
things in linux can write out to two output streams. stdout and stderr. when you redirect with a | or a > it by default just moves stdout. stderr still spills out to your screen.
its this way so your error messages don't get piped to an output file or something
2>&1 tells your program to redirect stderr to stdout (so the two streams are merged) -- so then when you pipe it they both go to the next program

I'm curious, how did you go about testing all these methods?
so from the design perspective, each test usually goes and scrapes some portion of the site to make sure the output is somewhat reasonable.
like enchantments showing up when you AF for lots of enchantments

Obviously there isn't a good way to test to see if the webpage fails, since the only time it will thrown an error is if there is actually an error

but I was able to see each test case to compare what was actually needed
so like I was able to scrape the page and find the average # of creatures
and was able to see if that number was the one i was actually trying to test
Technically I haven't found a way to *force* the test to fail
but each has it's own unique factors
like if a card name is not in the whole scraped section, when the filter says it should be, that will fail
if I wanted to force a fail, I'd just keep a local copy of a dynamic filter webpage, edit the html to where it should fail (but still renders), then read that in instead
